body.plain: Adele won the Song of the Year for “Hello”, written with and produced by Greg Kurstin, at the 59th Grammy Awards on February 12, 2017. It was her second time accepting this award, having won with “Rolling in the Deep” exactly 5 years earlier.

songs.lyrics:
2017 Grammy’s Song of the Year Speech Lyrics
Thank you very much. Thank you. First of all, I really do apologize for swearing. I just... this means... George Michael, I love him, it means a lot to me, so I'm really sorry if I offended anyone anywhere.
Everyone, this is Greg Kurstin. Give it up for Greg Kurstin. Thank you very much for this award. Thank you to the Academy, thank you to my record labels XL and Sony, thank you to my manager, Jonathan. I always get so nervous... And I'd like to thank Greg, because Greg kept coming to England for me, to work with me. And I was really hard work this record, had a very short attention span, and he would come to me in England so that I didn't have to leave my son, and yet you would leave your son and daughter. So thank you for your patience with me and for helping to create my favorite song I've ever done. So thank you, Greg

...Thank you to my mom and dad...Embed

songs.full_title: Adele's Billboard 200 Chart History by Adele
songs.title: Adele’s Billboard 200 Chart History

description.plain:
This is an annotated chart history of the British pop singer Adele. (As of now, it only includes US chart history.) It features all of her albums and EPs.

Note that songs are sorted by the year they were released, not necessarily in the year they peaked in. For example, 19 peaked at #4…in 2012. Also, 21 peaked at #1 in both 2011 and 2012, so which year would we put it in? The answer is its year of release: 2011.

All info is provided from Billboard.

songs.full_title: All I Ask by Adele
songs.title: All I Ask

description.plain:
“All I Ask” is a song by British singer-songwriter Adele, written about a potentially final escapade in a failing relationship. It was written in collaboration with Bruno Mars, Brody Brown and Philip Lawrence for her third album, 25.

The song received a relatively large amount of promo for a non-single: it was first performed live as a part of Adele: Live in New York City, and next in the Carpool Karaoke segment on The Late Late Show with James Corden.

However, some fans of Adele began associating a ‘curse’ with this song after its next promo spot, the 58th Grammy Awards. During Adele’s “All I Ask” performance there (which itself was a surprise, she had been expected to perform her then-latest single, “When We Were Young”), the piano microphones fell from their mounts and onto the strings, creating a loud clanging noise perceivable to the audience and multiple times louder yet in Adele’s earpiece. She bravely sung on, later consoling herself with some cheeseburgers and a redo performance on Ellen.
https://twitter.com/Adele/status/699457767896002561

Continuing the supposed curse, two months later, during a tour stop in Birmingham, UK, all of the arena’s speakers simultaneously stopped working during a performance of this same song. This time, Adele’s earpiece remained normal, though, so she didn’t realize the issue until afterward.
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1VpayD1UMwo

Coincidentally or not, Adele dropped “All I Ask” from her tour setlist on July 16, 2016, and has not performed it since.

songs.full_title: All Night Parking Interlude by Adele (Ft. Erroll Garner)
songs.title: All Night Parking Interlude
songs.title_with_featured: All Night Parking Interlude (Ft. Erroll Garner)

description.plain:
In her  interview for the November 2021 issue of Rolling Stone, Adele said that she was able to  briefly find love again after her divorce. There are a few songs on the album about this first relationship after her separation. The Erroll Garner-sampling “All Night Parking” one of these, an ode to the intoxicating feeling of falling for someone new.
Unfortunately, the romance was long-distance and doomed from the start.

[It] was a great learning curve and nice to feel loved, but it was never going to work.

“Another Love” is a song recorded by Adele in 2015, during the sessions of her third studio album, 25, but was ultimately scrapped.

The song made its way online on Valentine’s Day (February 14) of 2022.

songs.full_title: Be Divine (Main Mix) by Ricsta (Ft. Adele)
songs.title: Be Divine (Main Mix)

description.plain:
In a rare occurrence, Adele shows off her experimental side in this 2006 Ricsta track.

Her vocals are as strong as ever, but her generally soul/folk ballad-type production is taken away. In its place is an uptempo, heavily drum-based electronic song.

This song was released 2 years before her smash debut, 19, while she was still attending BRIT School. As a result, it isn’t very well-known. In fact, unlike most of her work, the lyrics are fairly braggadociously relationship-related. Most of her lyrics are more break-up, crushing, or just plain old “I love you” type.

songs.full_title: Best for Last by Adele
songs.title: Best for Last

description.plain:
“Best for Last” is a stripped-down acoustic track on Adele’s debut, 19. It sheds some light on the downfall of the relationship between Adele and her ex-boyfriend, which inspired almost all of the songs on the album.

Here, we see Adele has developed mixed feelings about this guy. On one hand, she’s realized that, despite her best efforts, her love for him will remain indefinitely unrequited—no matter what she does, he always “goes back” to an old flame. She’s palpably frustrated, and states that he’s not even good enough to treat her in such a way. In the choruses, she rails against her cheating lover who has made her feel unwanted by telling him that really, he’s the temporary one who doesn’t mean anything.

Yet everywhere else in the song, Adele is still attached to him. The way he mistreats her only makes her more eager to attract him, to the point where she’s stuck in a cycle of daydreaming about what he’ll say to her when it does work out… even as it still doesn’t.

songs.full_title: Can I Get It by Adele
songs.title: Can I Get It

description.plain:
Written about wanting to be in a real relationship instead of one that would devolve into casual sex, “Can I Get It” is a big production pop track created in collaboration with Shellback and Max Martin.

In her interview with Rolling Stone magazine, Adele shared how casual sex seemed to be the only thing the Los Angeles dating pool was good for. She jokingly shared that she “lasted five seconds [dating in LA].”

She also shared that she didn’t want to slip back into her old habits that come with casual dating and how it would do more damage than good.

songs.full_title: Can’t Be Together by Adele
songs.title: Can’t Be Together

description.plain:
“Can’t Be Together” is the second of three bonus tracks included on the Target Deluxe version of 30. The track, a piano-led ballad produced by frequent Adele collaborator Greg Kurstin, appears to exist tangentially to the chronological storyline Adele suggested defines the standard tracklisting.

Following her divorce, Adele appears to be considering her relationship with an old flame. She makes amends for past behavior, shares that she misses and loves the subject, but comes to the conclusion that they can’t be in a relationship and should focus on their current partners.

songs.full_title: Can't Let Go by Adele
songs.title: Can’t Let Go

description.plain:
“Can’t Let Go” is the first of three Target bonus tracks from singer-songwriter Adele’s third studio album, 25. The song was written by Adele and Linda Perry, who also contributed  by producing the track.

“Can’t Let Go” has never been discussed by Adele, beyond a response that it always makes her emotional when asked by a fan to perform it on tour. However, lines such as “this love, it ain’t over yet” imply a connection to an active relationship. Adele has confirmed her relationship with husband Simon Konecki has experienced some bumps, especially while writing and discussing other song “Water Under the Bridge”. As a result, it’s reasonable to assume this song is also about him.

songs.full_title: Chasing Pavements by Adele
songs.title: Chasing Pavements

description.plain:
On “Chasing Pavements”, Adele wonders whether or not to try and pursue a relationship with the man of her dreams. It actually caused a bit of controversy in the States because people thought “chasing pavements” was a euphemism for being in love with gay men (definitely unattainable for women).

Adele briefly explained the story behind this track in an interview with ELLE for their “Life in Lyrics,” saying:

“Chasing Pavements,” I slapped my boyfriend and was running down to Tottenham Court Road in London to make sure I didn’t get in trouble, and then no one was chasing after me, and I was, like, “You’re chasing pavements, it’s going nowhere.”

The song was Adele’s first big hit in the United States and earned the Brit one of her first Grammys (Best Female Pop Vocal Performance).

Rapper Machine Gun Kelly later used a sample from this song for his own “Chasing Pavements” off his self-released album Rage Pack.

songs.full_title: Cold Shoulder by Adele
songs.title: Cold Shoulder

description.plain:
Adele has already talked about daydreaming about a lover, one night stands and manipulation, and thinking about exploring a crush thus far on 19. However, she hasn’t gotten to a post-relationship song yet until now.

“Cold Shoulder” talks about an ex that cheated on Adele, yet she clearly still has feelings for. However, this guy is already seeing another girl, something that she clearly feels terrible about. However, in 21, she reciprocates those feelings to another ex.

songs.full_title: Crazy for You by Adele
songs.title: Crazy for You

description.plain:
According to Adele,  “Crazy For You” “is probably the only really nice song” on 19.

It is a joyful track and focuses on Adele’s love for a boy and how much she adores him over a soothing G Major guitar chord pattern performed by Adele herself.

songs.full_title: Cry Your Heart Out by Adele
songs.title: Cry Your Heart Out

description.plain:
“Cry Your Heart Out” is a crisp Motown-gone-reggae track with whimsical vocal effects and ad-libs. Disguised as an upbeat-pop track, “Cry Your Heart Out” is about depression.

In her interview with Zane Lowe for Apple Music, Adele shared that the song describes the time after her divorce when she felt like the whole world had ended and she became extremely depressed and lethargic. However, she admits that crying and outpouring is healthy and can help one to come out of that state of mind.

songs.full_title: Daydreamer by Adele
songs.title: Daydreamer

description.plain:
“Daydreamer” is the first track off Adele’s first album, 19.

In 2008 interviews with The Sun and Daily Star Adele discussed the song’s inspiration:

It was about a friend of mine, who’s still one of my best friends, and he was bi. But I started falling in love with him around my 18th birthday. He convinced me that it would be fine but that night he kissed one of my best boyfriends and I was like: ‘Get lost!’
I had no problem with him being bisexual, but I can’t fight off girls and boys. I get jealous enough as it is. It’s about everything I’d hoped he’d be and we’d be, but he would never be and we would never be. So, it’s me daydreaming about him.

description.plain:
“Don’t You Remember” – the fourth track on Adele’s 21, – follows Adele through her admission of her own personal flaws as she finds herself begging her ex-lover to recall why he initially fell in love with her.

Adele became increasingly aware that her bitterness after the break-up negatively altered her perspective of the relationship and her ex-lover which fueled the creation of this song.

You know when you forget why you loved someone? I was just thinking about how my entire body would just shiver if my ex touched me to say hello. It’s sad when you can’t remember why you loved someone.
-Adele, The Sun.

songs.full_title: Fastlove (Live at the 59th Grammys) by Adele
songs.title: Fastlove (Live at the 59th Grammys)

description.plain:
At the 59th Annual Grammy Awards on February 12, 2017, in addition to sweeping all 5 categories in which she was nominated, Adele performed a heartfelt tribute to the late George Michael. She covered “Fastlove”, originally appearing on his 1996 release, Older. The song was rearranged from an slinky dance track into a more solemn ballad with the help of Hans Zimmer.

About a minute into her performance, Adele stopped and restarted, declaring that she “can’t do it again like last year […] can’t mess this up for him”, in reference to her technical difficulty-ridden performance of 25 track “All I Ask” at the 2016 show.

A snippet of a studio recording of this cover was included in the opening credits of Freedom, a documentary about George Michael’s life and music career, airing October 16, 2017. As of this point, there has been no word from Adele or her label on an official release of the full studio version.

songs.full_title: First Love by Adele
songs.title: First Love

description.plain:
Adele is known for her chart-topping love songs. However, those songs tend to be dramatic, sad, ballad-like, and overall very emotional.

For “First Love”, the seventh track on her debut album 19, she tones it down—a lot. A celesta (what sounds like the bell) chimes throughout the song, which goes through no sort of increase in sound or climax. Clearly, it’s still about love, though.

According to author Marc Shapiro, her first love was a bisexual man who cheated on her with a man before they even started dating. (They had planned to date, though.) However, he did not say whether it influenced this song, and Adele has left no comment on his words.

That man inspired her song “Daydreamer”, however, it’s more likely this song is about the separate ex-boyfriend that inspired much of rest of 19.

songs.title: Hella O’s (Freestyle)

description.plain:
Using just two lines from an Adele song, Wiz drops a two minute freestyle with the same melody, yet completely different lyrics.

The song in question is “Hello”; the intro lines are from the second verse. However, instead of making a song about relationships, Wiz makes one about weed.

songs.full_title: He Won't Go by Adele
songs.title: He Won’t Go

description.plain:
“He Won’t Go” was mainly inspired by two friends of Adele’s that she had met after her first record, 19, was released. She had met them through her love of dogs. The male was a heroin-addict and had been making his journey to rehab. The couple’s bond had helped the male overcome his addiction, something that really touched Adele, who says that she is very proud of both of them, as the male has been “clean” for what is now over a year.

Adele spoke with The Sun about this:

The first verse was about me and my ex but then became about two of my close friends who are a couple that became my lifeline when I came off tour. Two months after I met them, the boyfriend went into rehab for heroin addiction. I had no idea about his problem.

songs.full_title: Hold On by Adele
songs.title: Hold On

description.plain:
In Adele’s cover story interview for the November 2021 issue of Vogue (US), interviewer Abby Aguirre previewed “Hold On” from Adele’s upcoming 30 album. The track was described by Aquirre as “a joyous anthem” with “gospelly” organ. The track ends with an amateur choir consisting of Adele’s friends singing “Just hold on.”

“The thing that they’re all singing is what my friends used to say to me,” Adele explains. “That’s why I wanted them to sing it, rather than an actual choir.”

On November 7, 2021, a snippet of the song debuted in a video advertisement for Amazon.

songs.title: Hometown Glory

description.plain:
“Hometown Glory” is Adele’s debut single, released on October 22, 2007. It is also the final track on her first album, 19. An understated love song to her hometown of West Norwood, South London, the singer wrote it in just 10 minutes at age 15 after having an argument wherein her mother tried to convince Adele to leave home to go to university in Liverpool.

The song was rereleased as a single on July 22, 2008 with this alternate cover:

songs.full_title: I Drink Wine by Adele
songs.title: I Drink Wine

description.plain:
In her interview with Rolling Stone magazine, “I Drink Wine” was described by Adele as a song about shedding one’s ego, complete with a bit of a Seventies Elton John and Bernie Taupin flair, sharing:

I took everything so personally at that period of time in my life, so the lyric ‘I hope I learn to get over myself’ is like [me saying] ‘Once I’ve done that, then maybe I can let you love me.’

Adele also pulled a “Barry Manilow trick,” on the song where every chorus is sung differently. She put on different characters while recording the background vocals, too, to give it a sarcastic, Sixties vibe.

It made it less intimidating because some of the things I’m talking about really hit home for a lot of people.

The track was debuted live ahead of the album release at Adele’s CBS Special One Night Only performed in LA alongside other tracks from the album.

songs.full_title: I Found a Boy by Adele
songs.title: I Found a Boy

description.plain:
“I Found a Boy” was the earliest song written to appear on 21, though Adele considers “Take It All” to be the first song written specifically for the record.

The song made its first appearances in 2009, two years before the album’s release, as part of the setlist of select shows of the An Evening With Adele tour. For these shows, she referred to it under a working title of “Stand By Me”.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ijSqgvhoQKo

Based on the timing (as well as her lack of information shared about the track) it’s unclear if she’s referring to having “found” the subject of 21 after breaking up with the subject of 19, or to having found someone else after breaking up with 21.

“I Found A Boy” appears as the twelfth track on the US iTunes and Japanese versions of 21.

songs.full_title: I'll Be Waiting by Adele
songs.title: I’ll Be Waiting

description.plain:
“I’ll Be Waiting” is a far more upbeat and hopeful song compared to the rest of 21. On it, Adele discusses how she can benefit from her recent breakup and apologizes for portraying her ex-lover in a negative light.

In an interview with Spin Magazine, she talked about how some of her songs were written as a “fuck you” to her exes. This song comes at a large contrast to that, as it’s more of a traditional love song than a “fuck you” breakup one.

songs.full_title: I Miss You by Adele
songs.title: I Miss You

description.plain:
“I Miss You” is the third track on 25 and fifth collaboration between Adele and Paul Epworth, having previously collaborated on “Rolling in the Deep”, “I’ll Be Waiting”, “He Won’t Go” and the James Bond theme song, “Skyfall.”

The song centers around intimacy of all kinds, and is likely Adele’s most erotic song to date. “When the lights go out” and Adele is left in the dark, she has numerous “doubts” about the state of her relationship. However, the physical intimacy at play distracts her from this increasing emotional discord.

songs.full_title: Love in the Dark by Adele
songs.title: Love in the Dark

description.plain:
Many might assume that “Love In The Dark” is yet another ode to the relationship that most of 21 is based on, however, it’s far more likely that this is based on the rebound relationship she fell into before she met “her man,” around the release of 21.

Unlike the main inspiration for 21, who has repeatedly been forgiven by Adele, she rarely refers to this guy in anything less than venomous tones in interviews and live recordings.

This song reflects how she felt at the time. Although he gave her what she needed at the time, someone to love her and look after her in her heartbreak, their relationship isn’t meant to continue. Adele finds herself in an uncomfortable position, given her history of being the one doing the breaking up.

songs.full_title: Love Is A Game by Adele
songs.title: Love Is A Game

description.plain:
In Adele’s cover story interviews for the November 2021 issues of Vogue UK and the Vogue US, interviewers Giles Hattersley and Abby Aguirre were previewed this final track from Adele’s 30 album. Hattersley reported:

She wants to play me a last song, the seven-minute opus that concludes the new album. It’s a knockout. A string-swirling, Garland-invoking, jazzy, campy, swooning delight, packed with world-weary end-of-the-show reflection, and featuring a vocal for the ages. She watches happily as I beam my way through listening to it. Breakfast at Tiffany’s was playing on the television in the studio when she recorded it, and she says it’s the end song the movie should have had. But it’s also the coda on her recent chapter.

Aguirre futher reported “the arrangement is whimsical and wall-of-sound retro, full of strings and vibrato and midcentury romance, but the lyrics deliver a subversive twist” and quoted Adele as explaining:

As [Breakfast at Tiffany’s] finished, we were trying to work out how to end the song, and I said, ‘We should write it as if we were writing the soundtrack—you know, at the end of the movie, where it pans out.’

songs.full_title: Melt My Heart to Stone by Adele
songs.title: Melt My Heart to Stone

description.plain:
Adele has said that “Melt My Heart to Stone” is her favorite song on the record, stating that: “I just love it. When I wrote it, I was crying. The song is about breaking up a relationship.”

She explained to The Guardian’s 1000 Songs Everyone Must Hear that “Melt My Heart to Stone” is “quite a sad song, it’s about giving everything for someone, which is what love is all about.”

She further noted that “all the words [in the song] came out in one take, as I was singing it.”

songs.full_title: Million Years Ago by Adele
songs.title: Million Years Ago

description.plain:
“Million Years Ago” is a song by English singer-songwriter Adele. It’s written by Adele in collaboration with Greg Kurstin and uses the melody from the song “Phantom of the Opera.”

Adele wrote the song after recently driving passing Brockwell Park in south London, where she grew up. Adele spent many hours of her youth in the park with her friends, often singing to them and playing the guitar.

Passing the park of her childhood moved her to tears, prompting her to write this song about missing her carefree days before fame.

songs.full_title: My Little Love by Adele
songs.title: My Little Love

description.plain:
In Adele’s cover story interview for the November 2021 issue of Vogue (US), interviewer Abby Aguirre previewed “My Little Love” and described it as having a “sexy ’70s groove” and “heavy strings”. Featured in the song are recorded conversations with Adele’s son Angelo in between verses, and a voicemail left for a friend as the outro.

She was inspired to incorporate voice notes by California rapper Tyler, the Creator and the British rapper Skepta, she explains. “I thought it might be a nice touch, seeing as everyone’s been at my door for the last 10 years, as a fan, to be like, Would you like to come in?”

“My Little Love” is about showing Angelo who his mother really is: a layered and complicated woman with an identity outside of their relationship, who’s struggled and cried and hurt.

songs.full_title: My Same by Adele
songs.title: My Same

description.plain:
“My Same” is an early Adele song, written about an opposites attract-type relationship she has with a best friend, writer Laura Dockrill.

The two had a major falling out around the time of 19’s conception, and did not reconcile until right before the release of 21. Adele discussed this history (with Laura in the audience) before performing “My Same” at her concert at the Royal Albert Hall on September 22, 2011:

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=x0qFPwwCwoM

Today, Adele and Laura remain friends.

songs.title: Need You Now (Live At CMT Artists Of The Year Awards)
songs.title_with_featured: Need You Now (Live At CMT Artists Of The Year Awards) (Ft. Darius Rucker)

description.plain:
Adele made (good) waves when she performed Lady Antebellum’s “Need You Now” with Darius Rucker for the 2010 CMT Artists of the Year special. They were subsequently nominated for Performance of the Year at the 2011 CMT Music Awards. Their cover of the song was also included on the Target deluxe edition of 21.

Check out Lady Antebellum’s page for “Need You now” to get the breakdown of all the lyrics

songs.full_title: Oh My God by Adele
songs.title: Oh My God

description.plain:
“Oh My God” explores Adele wanting to put herself first but having internal conflicts about it. Following the previous track, “Oh My God” finds Adele taking control of her life after a depressive episode in her life.

Following the release of 21 Adele’s fame shot through the roof however, she very quickly got into a relationship with Simon Konecki. And through the peak years of her career and fame, she was in a relationship. In “Oh My God,” Adele realizes that she is single and available for dating for the first time since becoming famous.

songs.full_title: One and Only by Adele
songs.title: One and Only

description.plain:
In this uptempo, bluesy ballad, Adele croons to a crush and asks them to be with her. It comes in as the ninth track on 21, her super-popular second album.

Although crush songs are certainly a staple on 19, most of 21 is generally about the aftermath of a relationship. It’s certainly interesting to see Adele recovering and moving on while sorting out her affairs with her previous, unnamed ex.

description.plain:
L'album le plus personnel qu'elle ait jamais écrit dans sa carrière. C'est ce que dit l'auteur-compositeur-interprète britannique dans plusieurs interviews publiées dans les jours précédant la sortie.
“Can I Get It” raconte ce que c'était que de penser à la possibilité de sortir avec une autre personne et d'établir une relation au-delà du sexe occasionnel.

songs.full_title: Remedy by Adele
songs.title: Remedy

description.plain:
“Remedy” was one of the early songs Adele worked on for 25, and she wrote it about her son, Angelo, as well as for other people she loves in her life. “I wrote it about my child,” she said to Rolling Stone. “But I sang it for everyone that I really love. When I wrote it, I got my confidence back in my writing ‘cause I believed in myself.”

The ballad, which Rolling Stone said “feels like Adele’s own version of Bob Dylan’s ‘Make You Feel My Love,’” was written by Adele in collaboration with Ryan Tedder for her third album 25. Tedder first confirmed his involvement in the album when he tweeted shortly after the commercial aired for the lead single “Hello.”

He previously worked with Adele on “Rumour Has It” and “Turning Tables”.

songs.full_title: Right as Rain by Adele
songs.title: Right as Rain

description.plain:
The eighth track on Adele’s debut 19 finds her lamenting on a lost love, much like the rest of the album. However, this somewhat embraces the pain of a bad relationship. It plays off of the idiom “right as rain”, which means satisfactory and good.

Back when it was a thing, this song was featured on her MySpace.

description.plain:
The “River Lea” is a real river that flows through the north and east of Adele’s childhood city of London. It also has a section named the River Lea Navigation, which is canalised.



Simplified diagram showing the River Lea from its source in the Chiltern Hills down its course to its mouth in the River Thames at Limehouse


In an interview with NPR, Adele discussed how the river is connected with her life.


A lot of my life was spent walking alongside the River Lea to go and get to somewhere else. It linked quite a lot of estates to each other, so that’s how you’d meet up with your friends.

The idea of the song is that, especially since I’ve become a parent, let alone writing this record, I’m dealing with myself for the first time. And I have a lot of bad habits. And rather than admitting that I have bad traits in my actual character, I blame it on where I’m from.

songs.full_title: Rolling in the Deep by Adele
songs.title: Rolling in the Deep

description.plain:
The 2012 song and record of the Year at the Grammy’s, “Rolling In The Deep” was described in an interview with Spin Magazine as a ‘gospel disco’ kiss-off to an unfaithful dude:

It’s me saying, ‘Get the fuck out of my house' instead of me begging him to come back.

The song hit number one in the US, where it became the biggest crossover hit in 25 years.

songs.full_title: Send My Love (To Your New Lover) by Adele
songs.title: Send My Love (To Your New Lover)
songs.title_with_featured: Send My Love (To Your New Lover)

description.plain:
Adele wrote “Send My Love (To Your New Lover)” in collaboration with Max Martin and Shellback for her third album 25.

Adele played guitar on the record, and it was this riff that began the song. She told the New York Times:

I’ve had that guitar bass line since I was, like, 15. I used to cover ‘Wonderful World’ doing that riff. It sings over it really well. With [the producers] Max Martin and Shellback, we knocked that out in a day.

This is a more upbeat, straight-pop record for Adele, which makes sense considering the super producers behind the sound. Prior to this record, however, Adele hadn’t heard of Max Martin or Shellback. It was listening to Taylor Swift with songwriter Ryan Tedder that led her to discover their prominence in the pop landscape.

This song was originally titled “We Ain’t Kids No More,” but at the last minute, at the encouragement of her manager, Adele decided to change it. She told Rolling Stone:

Otherwise, you might as well just call the fucking album Old.

(Given that a lot of the songs on this album are about nostalgia for childhood and the past.)

The song is directed toward the guy Adele dated between the subject of much of 21, and her husband, Simon Konecki. He previously inspired one other track, “One and Only”.

songs.full_title: Set Fire to the Rain by Adele
songs.title: Set Fire to the Rain

description.plain:
“Set Fire To The Rain” talks about a relationship coming to an end. Girl meets guy, he is wonderful and she falls really quickly. He tells her all of these amazing things, but really they were all a lie and now she is left with a broken heart. He continually tries to play games with her and no matter hard she fights, she will never win. Nothing she can do will fix the relationship.

As hard as she doesn’t want to let him go, she breaks it off in order to save herself for further heartbreak. The pain of breaking off a relationship with someone who means so much but is two-sided and not good to be with.

The title is an allusion to James Taylor’s “Fire and Rain,” but Adele approaches the same themes with a thug-feminist perspective.

In the US, the song hit #1, becoming her third consecutive number one from the album. She wouldn’t reach such heights again until her comeback single “Hello” debuted at number one with a shocking 1.12 million copies sold in one week – the largest ever recorded in the US.

songs.full_title: Someone Like You by Adele
songs.title: Someone Like You

description.plain:
“Someone Like You” is the second single off of Adele’s sophomore album, 21. The track was inspired by the broken relationship that inspired most of 21. As the closing track of the album, lyrically, it speaks of Adele coming to terms with it. She wrote it with Dan Wilson.

The single is one of Adele’s most commercially successful singles. It became Adele’s first number-one single in the UK and second in the USA. As of 2015, it is the third most downloaded single of all time in the UK and the fourth best-selling single of the 21st century.

Fun fact: This was the first pure-piano ballad to ever top the Billboard Hot 100. At the time of “Someone Like You’s” ascension, there were 1,008! The second was Bruno Mars' “When I Was Your Man.”

The song won the first ever Grammy Award for Best Pop Solo Performance, at the 54th Grammy Awards in 2012.

songs.full_title: Strangers By Nature by Adele
songs.title: Strangers By Nature

description.plain:
“Strangers By Nature” is a homage to Judy Garland and opens with Adele taking flowers to the cemetery of her own heart and wondering if she’ll ever learn “to nurture what I’ve done.” She co-wrote the song with Ludwig Göransson, an Oscar-winning Swedish composer who worked on Black Panther and with Childish Gambino.

They worked on “Strangers” after she had watched the Renée Zellweger-led Garland biopic, “Judy”, and wondered why no one wrote songs like that anymore. She calls the track her “Death Becomes Her” moment, alluding to the camp classic starring Meryl Streep and Goldie Hawn as two vengeful, youth-obsessed frenemies. Through “Strangers,” Adele acknowledges being a bit of a “hot mess.”

In her November 2021 interview with Brittany Spanos for Rolling Stone magazine, Adele revealed that the album’s tracklist is almost a chronological chain of events. The song is short and whimsical, is so unlike anything she’s done before that she almost thought about giving it to someone else to sing or sample.

songs.full_title: Sweetest Devotion by Adele
songs.title: Sweetest Devotion

description.plain:
“Sweetest Devotion” is a song by English singer-songwriter Adele. It’s written by Adele in collaboration with Paul Epworth, and appears as the final track on her third album, 25.

In an interview with USA Today, Adele stated that this song is about being a parent to her son, Angelo, who was born in 2012:

The song is all about my kid. The way I’ve described it is that something much bigger has happened in my life. I love that my life is now about someone else.

Adele has tried to protect her son from the consequences of having a famous mother. She and the child’s father, Simon Konecki, brought a successful privacy case against a UK-based paparazzi agency for publishing photos of her son during family outings.

songs.full_title: Tired by Adele
songs.title: Tired

description.plain:
“Tired” is perhaps the most un-Adele like track possible. However, it makes for a compelling listen.

In the track, her vocals (which have a notable British accent) take a backseat to the production. Eg White layers a light synth riff, a strong bassline, and violin over simple drums, guitar, and piano while Adele does what she’s known for: singing a universally relatable song about a relationship.

The song climaxes right before the bridge, where the strings build up and change time signature to become a sudden swell of instrumental emotion. Then, she continues on.

songs.full_title: To Be Loved by Adele
songs.title: To Be Loved

description.plain:
“To Be Loved” is the penultimate track on British singer Adele’s new album, 30. Instrumentally, the song is a simple, slow piano ballad with a BPM of 103.

Lyrically, the ballad piano track describes how the ups and downs of life appear and that it’s time to take sacrifices in life for the things that are most important.

The track was first previewed on social media on November 17, 2021, two days prior to the album’s release. In the video, Adele is seen demo-ing the then just-composed song with cowriter and producer Tobias Jesso Jr. During an interview with Zane Lowe for Apple Music, Adele admitted that she has only ever sung the song start-to-finish three times, including the video she posted to social media.

songs.full_title: Turning Tables by Adele
songs.title: Turning Tables

description.plain:
In “Turning Tables”, Adele vows she will never fall victim to her ex’s mistreatment again over a dramatic piano backing. It’s one of the many songs on 21 where the production and vocals seamlessly mold together, allowing a more interesting listen.

The song is the third track on 21, and the fifth and final single from the album in the UK. It’s also Adele’s second collaboration with Ryan Tedder, appearing directly after “Rumour Has It” on the tracklist of this same album, and almost 5 years before the release of “Remedy” on 25.

songs.full_title: Water Under the Bridge by Adele
songs.title: Water Under the Bridge

description.plain:
While the title of this songs sets up the expectation that it’s about a relationship that’s over, the opposite is actually the case. Adele confirmed in her Rolling Stone cover story that it’s about her relationship with Simon Konecki, the father of her son Angelo, whom she’s since married.

It was sort of about a relationship suddenly getting really, really serious, and then getting a bit frightened by it, and then realizing that ‘I think this must be right. This is the relationship that I want to be in for as long as I can possibly be in it.’

She also told Zane Lowe on Beats 1:

‘Water Under The Bridge’ is more like, I’m waiting for him to be horrible but I don’t think he’s going to be—waiting for the relationship to end, this is the relationship now that I’m going to be in. It was quite a ground-breaking moment.

Adele performed this song on The Tonight Show with Jimmy Fallon on November 25, 2015.

On November 1, 2016, it was confirmed by Billboard that “Water Under the Bridge” would be the fourth single released from 25.

songs.full_title: When We Were Young by Adele
songs.title: When We Were Young

description.plain:
Newly-returned pop icon Adele worked with songwriter Tobias Jesso Jr. and producer Ariel Rechtshaid on the “‘70s styled shimmery disco ballad” “When We Were Young,” the second single from her album 25. She indicated in her Rolling Stone feature that the Elton John inspired ballad was her favorite on 25.

The piano used on the recording belonged to iconic minimalist composer Philip Glass. The piano is in Jesso’s grandmother’s house. Adele explained, “It used to be this mad party house and for some reason [Glass’s] piano was there so we wrote the song on that.”

In a town hall interview for SiriusXM’s The Spectrum, Adele described the setting of “When We Were Young” as a party with old friends and acquaintances, with “everyone that you’ve ever fallen out with, everyone that you’ve ever loved, everyone that you’ve never loved…And you’re all thrown together at this party when you’re like 50, and it doesn’t matter and you have so much fun and you feel like you’re 15 again.”

description.plain:
“Why Do You Love Me” is the last bonus track from Adele’s third album 25. It was written jointly by Adele and Rick Nowels, and produced by Ariel Rechtshaid. It was included exclusively in the Target and Japanese deluxe editions.

Within the song, Adele references all four of the natural elements: water, earth, air, and fire.

songs.full_title: Wild Wild West by Adele
songs.title: Wild Wild West

description.plain:
“Wild Wild West” is the first of three bonus tracks included on the Target Deluxe version of 30. The upbeat, country-tinged track, cowritten and produced by Ludwig Göransson, appears to exist tangentially to the chronological storyline Adele suggested defines the standard tracklisting.

The lyrics, utilizing a great deal of old west slang, begin with Adele describing the circumstances that brought about the rest of the album: moving from London to Los Angeles, raising her son Angelo, marrying her longtime partner Simon Konecki… and then it all falling apart.

The rest of the song appears to be inspired by the new experiences Adele undertook in the the western United States and beyond in following her separation, including visiting the ocean in Santa Barbara,  climbing a mountain in Idaho with friends, and traveling to the Arizona desert, Jamaica, and Greece. Some of these were documented on the artist’s Instagram page.

songs.full_title: Woman Like Me by Adele
songs.title: Woman Like Me

description.plain:
A diss song through and through “Woman Like Me” jumps toward the end of Adele’s relationship. It finds Adele chiding her ex for being complacent, lazy, and insecure, wasting the potential of their relationship.

Adele has shared that “Woman Like Me” is the only track she wrote when she felt rage following her divorce. She delivers the message clearly and calmly, less pissed off than completely over the situation.

Much like the rest of the album, the lyrics in “Woman Like Me” are not only directed at her ex but also herself as she learned these things for herself on this journey.
